CNCP v1 26784
{
  "concept": "vuejs/core#12234: Prop type inference for `typeof Symbol()` is incorrect and breaks Vue runtime checks",
  "version": "1.0",
  "created_at": "2026-03-15T04:21:56.981703+00:00",
  "text": "Prop type inference for `typeof Symbol()` is incorrect and breaks Vue runtime checks\n\n### Vue version\r\n\r\n3.5.12\r\n\r\n### Link to minimal reproduction\r\n\r\nhttps://play.vuejs.org/#\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\n1. Export a symbol in a typescript file `a.ts`\r\n```ts\r\n// a.ts\r\nexport const MySmbol = Symbol();\r\n```\r\n2. In a Vue file `Comp.vue` with `<script setup lang=\"ts\">` import and use the symbol as prop type and default:\r\n3. Update the prop type to be a union of the symbol type and some other inferable type, e.g., `boolean`.\r\n4. Use the symbol as default value:\r\n```vue\r\n// Comp.vue\r\n<script setup lang=\"ts\">\r\nimport { MySmbol } from \"./a\";\r\n\r\nwithDefaults(defineProps<{\r\n  value?: typeof MySmbol | boolean;\r\n}>(), { value: MySymbol });\r\n</script>\r\n\r\n<template>\r\n  renders\r\n</template>\r\n```\r\n**==> Check the JS output, and you can see that only the `boolean` type of the type union is inferred:**\r\n```\r\n props: {\r\n    value: { type: [Boolean], default: MySymbol }\r\n  },\r\n```\r\n5. Switch to `Prod` mode\r\n6. Create a second component, import and use the first component:\r\n```vue\r\n// App.vue\r\n<script setup>\r\nimport Comp from \"./Comp.vue\";\r\n</script>\r\n\r\n<template>\r\n  <Comp />\r\n</template>\r\n```\r\n7. Switch to `DEV` mode.\r\n**==> Now you will get the error: `can't convert symbol to string`**\r\n\r\n**Why is the DEV mode switching relevant?**\r\nWe are building a component library and there we use symbols as explicit defaults for special default behaviors.\r\nThis issue was only encountered when a user tried to develop (in dev mode) using the compiled lib (in prod mode).\r\n\r\nSee also: https://github.com/SchwarzIT/onyx/issues/1980#issuecomment-2426292759\r\n\r\n### What is expected?\r\n\r\n- The symbol type should be inferred correctly or no runtime check at all should be happening:\r\n```\r\n props: {\r\n    value: { type: [Symbol, Boolean], default: MySymbol }\r\n  },\r\n```\r\nor\r\n```\r\nprops: {\r\n    value: { default: SYMBOL }\r\n  },\r\n```\r\n- No error when a (PROD) compiled component is used for development\r\n\r\n### What is actually happening?\r\n\r\nVue's compiler inferred the prop type used for runtime validation as `Boolean`, even though the typescript type is `typeof unique symbol | boolean`. This causes the runtime validation to fail and trying to log an error. Because Vue tries to create an error message using implicit string conversions and symbols cannot be implicitly [converted to a string,](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Symbol/toString#description) the JS runtime throws: `Uncaught (in promise) TypeError: can't convert symbol to string`\r\n\r\n\r\n### System Info\r\n\r\n```shell\r\nSystem:\r\n    OS: macOS 13.6.7\r\n    CPU: (10) arm64 Apple M1 Max\r\n    Memory: 81.38 MB / 32.00 GB\r\n    Shell: 5.9 - /bin/zsh\r\n  Binaries:\r\n    Node: 20.17.0 - ~/Library/Caches/fnm_multishells/37685_1729492712079/bin/node\r\n    Yarn: 3.4.1 - ~/Library/Caches/fnm_multishells/37685_1729492712079/bin/yarn\r\n    npm: 10.8.2 - ~/Library/Caches/fnm_multishells/37685_1729492712079/bin/npm\r\n    pnpm: 9.7.1 - ~/Library/Caches/fnm_multishells/37685_1729492712079/bin/pnpm\r\n    bun: 1.1.21 - ~/.bun/bin/bun\r\n  Browsers:\r\n    Brave Browser: 122.1.63.169\r\n    Edge: 130.0.2849.46\r\n    Safari: 17.5\r\n```\r\n\r\n\r\n### Any additional comments?\r\n\r\nWe try to use symbols as explicit defaults in place of `undefined`, because the implicit default for `boolean` is `false`.\r\n\r\nYou can find playground examples with different usages of unique symbols here:\r\nhttps://play.vuejs.org/#__PROD__",
  "language": "en",
  "keywords": [
    "🔩 p2-edge-case"
  ],
